Lesson 5-C: Heatmap for Visualising and Analysing Multivariate Data

1.0 Getting Started

Install and launch the following R packages

pacman::p_load(seriation, dendextend, heatmaply, tidyverse)

2.0 Data

Loading the data to the R environment by using read_csv() function of readr package

wh <- read_csv("chap05/data/whdata2018.csv")

Change the rows by country name instead of row number by using the code chunk below:

wh$Country <- make.unique(as.character(wh$Country))
row.names(wh) <- wh$Country

The data was loaded into a data frame, but it has to be a data matrix to make a heatmap. The code chunk below will be used to transform wh data frame into a data matrix.

wh1 <- dplyr::select(wh, c(3, 7:12))
wh_matrix <- data.matrix(wh1)

3.0 Static Heatmap

3.1 heatmap() of R Stats

wh_heatmap <- heatmap(wh_matrix, Rowv=NA, Colv=NA)
wh_heatmap <- heatmap(wh_matrix)
wh_heatmap <- heatmap(wh_matrix, scale="column", cexRow = 0.6, cexCol = 0.8, margins = c(10, 4))

3.2 Creating Interactive Heatmap

heatmaply(mtcars)
heatmaply(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)])

3.2.1 Scaling method

heatmaply(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)], scale = "column")

3.2.2 Normalising method

heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]))

3.2.3 Percentising method

heatmaply(percentize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]))

3.3 Clustering Algorithm

3.3.1 Manual Approach

heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), dist_method = "euclidean", hclust_method = "ward.D")

3.3.2 Statistical Approach

wh_d <- dist(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), method = "euclidean")
dend_expend(wh_d)[[3]]
  dist_methods hclust_methods     optim
1      unknown         ward.D 0.5419990
2      unknown        ward.D2 0.6049647
3      unknown         single 0.5740665
4      unknown       complete 0.6152361
5      unknown        average 0.6985188
6      unknown       mcquitty 0.6311738
7      unknown         median 0.6035810
8      unknown       centroid 0.6554961
wh_clust <- hclust(wh_d, method = "average")
num_k <- find_k(wh_clust)
plot(num_k)
heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), dist_method = "euclidean", hclust_method = "average", k_row = 3)

3.3.3 Seriation

heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), seriate = "OLO")
heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), seriate = "GW")
heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), seriate = "mean")
heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), seriate = "none")

3.3.4 Working with color palettes

heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), seriate = "none", colors = Blues)

3.3.5 The Finishing touch

heatmaply(normalize(wh_matrix[, -c(1, 2, 4, 5)]), Colv=NA, seriate = "none", colors = Blues, k_row = 5, margins = c(NA,200,60,NA), fontsize_row = 4, fontsize_col = 5, main="World Happiness Score and Variables by Country, 2018 \nDataTransformation using Normalise Method", xlab = "World Happiness Indicators", ylab = "World Countries")
